reviewText:
Disclosure: I received a pre-release copy. Completed with 'Ending A: On the Run' during first playthrough.

Downfall (2016) is a very good adventure game that is in line with The Cat Lady and even the original Downfall, at once not bound by its predecessor and yet faithful to it. Players unfamiliar with the the formerly mentioned games will miss a number of tie-ins but should not feel like they are missing part of the game. Players familiar with the formerly mentioned games will be in for a real treat.

Negative Points
Sound
-There is an issue with audio popping/static on the default settings that I encountered in the non-Steam version, easily fixed and which I wrote a fix for in the Steam just in case others come across it;*
-there is an issue with volume leveling throughout the game, where the music will at times overwhelm the dialogue and vice-versa. This is something that Rem is looking into for a post-release patch;
-voice acting ranges from fantastic (actors for Adult Joe, Agnes/Young Ivy) to poor (Young Joe, Adult Joe's and Adult Ivy's screams). The voice acting is generally quite good, however the bit in the Prelude (sans Young Ivy, who was fantastic) and the two bits involving Adult  Joe and Adult Ivy screaming at different points are worth mentioning because the rest of the voice acting is so good. The issues seems to owe to not using soundproofing during the recording, as Adult Joe's scream is notably muted and Adult Ivy's sees the actress notably standing away from the microphone. Young Joe's lines are generally delivered in a choppy or stilted form, however there are some lines that are delivered well.

Narrative
-Players unfamiliar with The Cat Lady will be able to make sense of the latest parts of the game without issue, however they will not be able to enjoy the narrative tie-ins as they appear in earlier and later parts of the game.

Gameplay
-Players familiar with the original Downfall may lament the lack of combat (yes, the original point-and-click adventure game had a few combat and chase scenes) and the absence of puzzles (e.g. Dr. Z's mannequin). This is a matter of personal preference given that some of the puzzles in the original were obtuse, which contributed to pacing issues;
-the camera motion and 'follower' movement (Young Ivy and Agnes) lurches in a distracting fashion, leaving a number of scenes feeling cut off (e.g. the children discovering X marks the spot in the Prelude) and giving multi-character movement a sense of awkwardness;
-solutions to most scenes will be known to those that played the original Downfall and this can detract from the game for players that are sensitive to spoilers.

Positive Points
Sound
-The music is, once again, superb and maintains the same high quality as the original Downfall and The Cat Lady insofar as meeting the overall tone of a given scene and the way one scene flows into the next;
-sound effects are appropriate (not overdone, too frequent, or off-sounding) and in sync with the animations. This should not need mentioning, however this is a problem with any number of video games across all genres and therefore a strong point for a small development team;
-the addition of voice acting really brings the game alive in a way different from the original Downfall. The voice actors generally do quite a good job, with a strong notable mention being the voices in the Paradise of Rotting Flesh.

Visual Design
-The mixed-media-meets-graphic-novel approach that had its origins in the original Downfall and was greatly improved in The Cat Lady see further improvement here. The sickly and ominous sepia wash in the Prelude is just as poignant as the sparse use of colour outside of the prelude, cementing the chosen approach to visual design;
-Quite Haven Hotel is easily reminiscent of the version in the original Downfall. The game world consisting of the hotel and other properties is at once a bit larger (extra rooms/corridors) while at the same time smaller (no movie studio), however on the whole the game world is a bit larger and the parts are better integrated than the original Downfall. Further, the room designs all retain the same core theme from the original Downfall while having noticeable differences, irrespective of whether an element in a room is added to/removed or whole rooms are added/removed. Players that are unfamiliar with the original Downfall will neither recognise nor miss these elements, while players familiar with it will be able to take joy in recognising the alterations.

Narrative
-The characters are all incredibly vivid and relatable. We know or know of someone like Harrison and 'Birthday Sophie', Joe and Ivy, Joe's father, and all the other characters. Some of their mannerisms seem exaggerated, but that is the point and proof of their relatability: a surprising number of people really are that way;
-Joe, like Susan in The Cat Lady, initially questions the surreal environment but soon comes to accept it. The implications of this will not go unnoticed by more critical players interested in exploring the game's themes and metaphors;
-the heavy themes explored in the game are balanced by an appreciable level of sardonic humour, something that was absent in the original Downfall and lightens what could potentially be a too oppressive mood for some players;
-the blender scene. Period.

Gameplay
-Players unfamiliar with the original Downfall will be able to enjoy a game that features the clear pacing of The Cat Lady and players familiar with the original will be able to appreciate the much clearer pacing when recalling the original. The gameplay is seamless and fast-paced, both incredibly appropriate given the game's narrative;
-the game is unburdened by obtuse or frustrating gameplay elements which typified point-and-click adventure games, allowed players to immerse themselves in the narrative and focus on plot points-as-gameplay-decisions rather than pixel hunting and the like. This may seem like a problem to players looking for a more typical point-and-click adventure game, however it is important to understand that Harvester Games aimed at this approach rather than the more typical one and, thus, they succeeded at doing what they aimed to do all along.

Meta-Game
-Downfall (2016) seems to indicate the idea of creating a shared universe given The Cat Lady tie-ins. If this is actually the case players familiar with all three games are in for a real treat when it comes to the fourth game in what would be the trilogy;
-players of either or both the original Downfall and The Cat Lady will find the shared universe, and retained/cross-over elements (e.g. the dress mannequin) to be rewarding. These elements are well done and do not get in the way of or otherwise obscure the narrative. Downfall (2016) is a game that stands on its own, but is a game that is very much for fans of what we can likely call 'the series'.
